name: 1',4'-dihydrospiro[cyclohexane-1,3'-isochromen]-1'-ol
source: Karthikeyan M.; Glen R.C.; Bender A. General melting point prediction based on a diverse compound dataset and artificial neural networks. J. Chem. Inf. Model.; 2005; 45(3); 581-2475
Reason: The structure of the compound 1',4'-dihydrospiro[cyclohexane-1,3'-isochromen]-1'-ol consists of several notable features that will influence its melting point. Firstly, the presence of the spirocyclic element which connects a six-membered cyclohexane and a chromene ring will contribute to a rigid structure, increasing the melting point. Secondly, the presence of an alcohol (hydroxyl) functional group can lead to intermolecular hydrogen bonding, which generally raises the melting point. However, the compound also contains aromatic rings which can provide some degree of stabilization through delocalized π-electrons, but it might not necessarily elevate the melting point significantly compared to aliphatic rings. Considering benzene (as a known reference point for aromatic rings) has a melting point of 5.5°C and cyclohexane (as a reference for aliphatic rings) has a melting point of 6.5°C, the final prediction for the melting point must take into account the combined effect of molecular rigidity, hydrogen bonding, and aromatic stabilization. The prediction should consider: Base melting point (similar to cyclohexane): +6.5; Spirocyclic structure: +30 (due to increased rigidity); Hydrogen bonding from alcohol functional group: +20 (due to intermolecular hydrogen bonds); Aromatic ring: +10 (some contribution but less due the spiro fusion reducing resonance in the ring).
Prediction: The predicted melting point considering the addition of corresponding values would be 6.5 (base) + 30 (spirocyclic) + 20 (hydrogen bonding) + 10 (aromatic ring) = 66.5°C.
